course: Location: Orange County
notes:
This camp is designed to bring together juniors aged 10 to 18 from Southern California and Nevada, who wish to race in 2014 or have previous racing experience. Through social and educational modules juniors will: learn or relearn skills, go on a group ride with juniors in the same age group and/or ability level, and learn about preparation for racing. This educational weekend camp will start off the season properly for juniors racing in the SCNCA sphere, while keeping the atmosphere light and fun, saving the competition for race days in 2014.

Per SCNCA for attending junior camp:
2 upgrade points per day for a cat 4-3 upgrade
1 race credit per day for a 5-4 upgrade

title: Criterium Skills Clinic powered by CCSD
description:
Criterium Skills Clinic powered by CCSD will be held from 9:00am to 11:30am on Sunday, January 12, 2014. Registration is $35 and opens on December 7 via the USAC registration portal. Registration link will post here, when it goes live. Clinic limited to 30 athletes. This clinic will be located on the Huennekens criterium course in Mira Mesa, San Diego.

This clinic is coached by Level 1 USAC coaches, plus a former professional cyclist. By attending the complete program, athletes receive 2 qualifying race days for a category 5 to 4 upgrade, or 2 upgrade points for a category 4 to 3 upgrade.

title: 2014 UCI Track World Cup - Guadalajara, Mexico
Rokform / Rock 'n Road Junior Camp
description:
Rokform / Rock 'n Road Junior Team Camp:

WHO:  Rokform / Rock 'n Road Junior Development Team Members (+ parent volunteers, coaches, pros, sponsors, USAC, etc.)

WHAT: Three day camp for training, team building, skills building, and FUN

WHERE: Santa Maria, Sisquoc, Solvang and surrounding rural roads.  SCENIC, Challenging and SAFE.   NEW for 2014, our hotel "base location" is the Holiday Inn Hotel & Suites  (we outgrew our old location!!).  We have two meeting rooms; perfect for breakout sessions and bike storage.   

WHY: Junior development, safety and skills building, mentoring, developing the next generation of cyclists and for the fun of it!

WHEN: January 18, 19, 20 (Martin Luther King Holiday weekend).  Arrive late on the 17th.  Conclude with a ride to Solvang on the 20th (which requires some logistics effort to get cars that were left back at Santa Maria... we have drivers and shuttles planned).
notes:
PRELIMINARY AGENDA (subject to change):

Saturday:
- Group ride to Sisquoc for a short ITT.  Results from the TT allow us to break the group into skill-appropriate ride groups.

-  Separated group rides back to Santa Maria
-  Lunch / Joint meeting
-  Lectures (broken out into age / skill-appropriate topics)
    -Beginning racing (younger / beginner)
    -Race / Team Tactics & Strategies (older / experienced)
    -Mechanical training / safety checks / derailleur adjustment
    -SafeSport program (USAC-led by Jon Whiteman via Skype)
    -Sponsor information / Team Benefits

Sunday:
-  Drill sessions (alternate groups with lecture sessions)
-  Slow speed drills
    -Bottle pickup / bunny hop / bump drills
-  High speed cornering drill
-  Lecture sessions
    -USADA / RaceClean
    -Nutrition Seminar conducted by Dr. Allen Lim
    -4th annual Europe Race Trip details
        -UCI 2.1 4-day stage race "Sint-Martinusprijs" in Belgium
        -Kermesse racing
        -Training in Flanders
        -Touring
        -Tour de France stage visit
        -Opportunity for two to stay the summer with our associated Belgian Junior Team

-  Group ride to Sisquoc
-  TTT course training with pro / coach leaders
-  TTT 
-  Lunch at Sisquoc School
-  Photo Shoot
-  Afternoon group rides (age / skill appropriate groups) ending back at Santa Maria
 
-  Dinner
-  Fun evening event at Boomers Arcade Center

Monday:
-  SPLIT RIDE SESSIONS
    -Elite "A" and "B" team doing one ride
    -All regular members split into their age / skill groups for rides
    -All rides ending at Solvang in mid afternoon

title: Reno Cycling Team Training Camp Series
description:
This training camp series is designed to teach avid cyclists a variety of training 
methods so each rider will gain a deeper understanding into their own strengths and weaknesses, and be better prepared to make future training decisions. With this knowledge, riders will gain confidence in meeting their own training needs and have tools to design their own training plan.

Riders should have enough riding endurance to complete a 50 mile ride at any pace, and have a functional understanding of group bike handling skills like drafting, holding a line, pace-lines and obstacle awareness. The camp is designed to accommodate riders of all fitness levels.

title: WCC Conference Championships Presented by Fresno State Bulldog Cycling
Echelon Gran Fondo - Sonoma
description: It’s home to Wine Spectator’s Wine of the Year, and to more than 500 wineries. It boasts two of only 10 Michelin three-star restaurants in the United States. Oh yeah… it also produces Beer Advocate’s best beer in the world. If you haven’t enjoyed yourself enough — or perhaps too much — perhaps you’ll spend a day in one of 70 spas or 50 golf courses. Or just float down the Russian River… And of course, this is the epicenter of American cycling. Professional riders, bike builders and weekend warriors alike know that this the epitome of cycling grandeur. Rolling vineyard-covered hills. Dense canopy-sheltered roadways. Immaculate coastlines. Redwoods. No cars in sight.
course: Our course starts and finishes in the heart of Sonoma, on the historic town square that showcases the town’s Mexican colonial past and was once the capital of the California Republic. From the start riders will exit town to the East, and within just a couple miles will be rolling into Napa County. Mini riders will enjoy a flat course out and back. The Gran and Medio riders will get a warm-up incline at mile 15, with the first real challenge at mile 22, where you’ll gain 1100 feet in 7 miles, drop 700 feet fast, then climb 1000 feet again. Gran riders face another 800 feet just past the Glen Ellin rest stop, then it’s a relatively easy pedal back to celebr-…er, civilization.
notes: Upon return to Sonoma, the finest offerings await. More than a dozen local restaurants provide riders with replenishment. Joining them are the eager representatives of the Sonoma Vintners & Growers Alliance, and a handful of the county’s famous brewers. See our Party page for developing details.

title: 805 Criterium Weekend Hancock Twilight
description:
Welcome to the home of the 805 Criterium Weekend!  We’ve grown again in 2014 with the addition of the Hancock Twilight Crit on Friday. Our 805 Crit Weekend, isn’t small time either, as we’ll have a projected $35,000 in cash and prizes up for grabs May 9th, 10th and 11th!! That includes preems! This is just the start.  Don’t be surprised to see us add a 4th day in 2015. We ask you, the racer, to support our efforts to build such a high quality event that it attracts racers from throughout the USA in the future, by making every effort to show up this year on Friday. Get your day off, set up the family for the weekend and bring them all to the beautiful wine country of the Central Coast to celebrate American Style Crit racing in awesome public venues and of course Mother’s Day!
 
The 805 Crit Weekend benefits the Lompoc Police Foundation and the Santa Ynez Valley Humane Society, two very worthy non-profit organizations that do valuable work in their communities. In addition to those charities the weekend is supported by members of The Santa Barbara Bicycle Club, Team One Way, The Village Dirtbags, The Dirt Club, SYVCC, Woody’s Butcher Block Masters, Tailwinds BC and Col Vento Cycling Club. We’re building great community events as well as a National Class Bike Race. There will be Firestone 805 Beer Garden’s, expo booths and food at all three races. At Saturday and Sunday there will be Free Kids Races as well, it is fun for the whole family. At the Lompoc Valley of Flowers race on Sunday, Mother’s Day, we will celebrate Mothers by giving the 1st 500 Moms a red rose!
 
This year not only will there be individual prize lists for each day of racing, but we will run the 805 Criterium Weekend as a Series with a point structure (top 10 point schedule of 15, 12, 10, 8, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1 each day, a mid race 5, 3, 1 bonus sprint on the last day only, tiebreaker is place on the last day) that will crown winners 5 deep in each Series Category. These Categories are identified in the schedule below. Racers can enter each day of racing, or enter the entire series. In order to be eligible for the Overall Series Prize List racers must compete in all 3 days of racing in one category. We have a ton of great sponsors that help make this happen, so please support them when possible. Sunday’s Lompoc Valley of Flowers had been awarded the SCNCA State Elite Criterium Championships, and as such the event has been granted permission to allow Continental Pro Team Rider to race that day, however they will not be eligible for the SCNCA Title or Jersey, but will still be in the running for the event and Series Overall Prize lists.
 
PRIZES:
This is a USA Cycling Cat C Race. Pro 1/2, 35+ 1-4, 45+ 1-4, W 1,2,3 : All CASH All other prizes are CASH, merchandise and/or awards. 55/60+ picked separately and separate prizes. W3/4 picked separately w/ separate prizes, and points to be used towards upgrading, however Socal Cup Points will be based on the combined finish. All Jr. Races will be picked separately.
course:
Courses:
805 Friday Hancock Twilight: This is a brand new course! It is a 1 mile Oval Banked two lane training track that will be very fast! Deceivingly difficult, but full on for the entire race.
805 Buellton Avenue of Flags Criterium: “L” shaped, 6 corner course with a small hill. Fast sprint. Great for spectators! Start Finish located at Second and the Avenue of Flags.
805 Lompoc Valley of Flowers SCNCA Elite Criterium Championships: This is a 1.25 mile, “Figure 8” course with, well 8 corners. 6 Rights, 2 Lefts. It is flat as a pancake and very fast with one tight right turn that requires your attention.


Pit:
SRAM will again be there with their awesome mechanics and providing wheels and support for all of the racers
registration:
REGISTRATION:
Friday Starts at 12:30pm, 1 hr. before each start and closes 15 min. prior to race. Saturday and Sunday Starts at 6:00am, 1 hr. before each race and closes 15 min. prior to race. 2nd race is $20 after the higher fee is paid. $10 Late Fee Applies on entries after 05/07/14. Registration Tent will be located within 100 feet of Start Finish Line Each Day. This is also where racer staging and the awards ceremonies will take place. Online Registration at www.usacycling.org 

Registration will be open 1 hr prior to and will close 15 mins before race starts and located near the start finish line.
SNAIL MAIL PRE-REGISTRATION:
Please make all checks payable to Lompoc Police Foundation and mail with a standard USAC release form to:
805 Criterium Weekend, C/O Lisa Tonello, P.O. Box 67, Los Alamos, CA 93440
notes:
Special Rules:
*SoCal Cup Cats. … 3Day +Series - Riders must compete in all 3 races to qualify for GC Purse. Minimum 50% PAYOUT FOR ALL PURSES INCLUDING Series General Classification Purse & Require 60% Full Fields for 100% Payout, CAT 5, W3/4 & Junior fields are 75, Pro 1/2 is 125 and all others are 100. Sunday's Valley of Flowers Crit is the SCNCA Elite Criterium Championship and eligible categories are represented in the BLUE boxes above. State Championships are open to anyone who has a current USAC license and are either US Citizens or Permanent Resident Aliens. Only those that have the SCNCA listed on their license can win the title. The SCNCA will allow both men and women from Continental Pro Teams to race, however they will be ineligible for the title, jersey or medals. Online Reg at www.usacycling.com. Snail Mail Entries with Standard USAC Wavier by May 5th, 2014. After this add $10 Late Fee per race day.
See you at the fastest growing race series in the West!
directions:
MapQuest this: One Hancock Drive
Lompoc, CA 93436

The Parnassus Investments Burlingame Criterium
description: The Burlingame Criterium is an exciting race for cyclists of all levels, with tight turns and a sprint finish. Whether this is your first or 100th race, you will find it both challenging and rewarding. Also, children 12 & under can ride on the same course as the pros at Ryan's Ride, a charitable cycling event for kids, dedicated to the memory of Ryan Phua. Proceeds benefit the Livestrong Foundation to support cancer programs in the Bay Area.
course: The 2014 course is different than recent years due to construction in the downtown Burlingame Area. The 0.71 mile circuit (about the same length as the traditional course) starts on Bellevue Ave, next to the Burlingame Library. It then runs counterclockwise making an immediate left onto Primrose Rd, then a hard right onto Chapin Ave. You get a long straight down Chapin, but then brake hard for a tight, left-handed hairpin and reverse back up the other side of Chapin. A small right/left chicane cuts across Primrose and brings you onto the straights of Donnelly Ave which ends in a hard left onto Lorton and transitions in a sweeping left hand turn back to Bellevue Ave. Chances are this last sweeping left will be a VERY fast section as everyone accelerates for great primes and the final sprint finish.
notes: Held  under USAC rules and permit.
directions:
Race day registration will be in front of the Burlingame Zoning and Planning building at 501 Primrose Rd, Burlingame CA. Please find parking along California Drive

Race Parking: Please follow the signs on California Drive and park only in the designated area which is the Cal Train parking lot.

title: San Rafael Twilight Criterium
description:
On July 26th, the speed and adrenaline of professional cycling returns to the streets of San Rafael. Prepare 
yourself for the pageantry of the criterium style of racing -- short, fast, urban and gritty. Absorb the 
romanticism of a twilight race -- part fading sun, part Downtown Lights. This isn’t cycling you watch. This is 
cycling you feel.
course:
The 1-km course, located in San Rafael’s vibrant downtown setting, starts and finishes on 4th Street while 
running clockwise on 4th, D St., 5th St., and A St. The Expo will occupy C St. between 4th & 5th St.
registration:

All fields are limited and will sell-out. Please register early. No phone or faxed entries will be accepted. All 
participants will sign a waiver/release form at registration. Those under 18 years old require a parent's or 
guardian's signature. USA Cycling sanctioned. Riders must present a current USA Cycling license at 
registration. Competitor age is determined by the age of the rider on Dec. 31, 2014.  There are no refunds or transfers. If available, on-site registration will assess a $10 late fee.
notes: Neutral Technical support will be provided by SRAM.
directions:

is between Lootens & E St on 4th St.

title: C510 Super Cat (Fundraiser for Alameda Co. Food Bank)
description:
The C510 Super Cat is an adventure style alley cat bike event through the East Bay, designed by the C510 bike club.  The start and end point will be in Joaquin Miller Park in Oakland.  

There will be 4 or 5 checkpoints along the course which each athlete must cross, but how each rider gets to and from these checkpoints and to the finish is completely open.  Choose your own adventure.

Checkpoint information will be given out the morning of the event.  There will be a barbeque, beverages and schwag at the end of the event.  The fastest finisher to cross all checkpoints will win the coveted Chrome jersey!

Aside from having a great day of riding in the gorgeous East Bay hills, this event will help to raise awareness and money for the Alameda Food Bank.  We encourage all entrants to raise $50 for the Alameda Foodbank.  More information on how to raise money can be found on the C510 facebook page: www.facebook.com/crocker510.
Meeting and course discussion is at 8am.  The ride will start promptly at 9am.
course: The course will be in the East Bay Hills.  There will be 4 checkpoints along the way.  Participants will be provided with the check points as they get to the next one.  The ride will start and finish at 'Meadow Area' in Joaquin Miller Park in Oakland.
registration:
Pre-register online for $20+registration fee at:http://www.brownpapertickets.com/event/801131
Register on site at day of event for $30.  
All entrants are strongly encouraged to raise or donate a minimum of $50 for the Alameda County Food Bank.  Information on fundraising is available online.
directions: Start of the ride will be at the Meadow Area in Joaquin Miller Park.  3600 Joaquin Miller Road in Oakland.  Take exit 2 (Joaquin Miller or Lincolin Ave) on Highway 13 in Oakland.  Proceed up (East) Joaquin Miller Road.  Park in Meadow Area on the left side of the Joaquin Miller Road (when traveling uphill) about 3/4 of a mile from Hwy 13.

title: LAGP World Record Attempt Day p/b LAVRA
USA Cycling Beginning Racer Program
description:
USAC BRP is open to Category 5 licensed racers over the age of 16, and is designed to develop a rider’s bike racing skills, allowing for safer and more enjoyable racing experiences. Riders who complete both the clinic and race portion will earn upgrade points, or have the events count as mass finishes. For a Category 5 racers, one (1) clinic completion counts as two (2) mass start finishes. This program was developed and modeled after the Northern California Early Bird Racing Series, directed by Larry Nolan, Laurel Green, Matt McNamara, John Cheetham, and Dan Smith.

Category 5 cyclists may upgrade to Category 4 by obtaining ten (10) points (race days). These points can be achieved by finishing 10 mass start races, or by completing five (5) USAC approved BRP clinics, or a combination of both. Mass start races count as one (1) point for each completed race and USAC approved BRP clinics count as two (2) points for each clinic.
course:
Each clinic Includes:
*On and off the bike training with USA Cycling Level 1 coaches and mentors
*30-minute training practice race
*Five (5) take-home training workouts and handouts
*Additional skills and sprinting workouts via *Trainingpeaks™ (code will be provided)
*Mechanic on hand for quick adjustments

Show up prepared with cycling clothing, bicycle, helmet, and any other items you need for riding your bike. Bring your own water and snack. This clinic is a participation based clinic, so being ready to ride is important to get the maximum out of your participation.

Agenda:
8:45am: Check in
9:00am: Introduction and Safety
9:15am: Begin instruction
10:30am: Training Practice Race
11:15am: Post-Training Race Debrief, Q&A and Wrap Up
12:00noon: Clinic complete

All participants must be USAC licensed, sign a release form, and wear a helmet.

title: US Paralympics Cycling Track National Championships
Ninja Night Race 3
description:
The first of its kind: a USAC sanctioned night mountain bike race series.

    Route Options For All Abilities
    Free T-Shirt For The First 50 Registrants
    Free Tamales For All Racers
    Live Band Rockin' Out The Start Finish Area
    Spectator Friendly Event With Bleachers
    Race 2 Starts On The San Diego Velodrome
course:
The courses are slightly different for Cat 3 and Pro / Cat 1-2.  The Cat 3 riders have a ‘short-cut’ up the infamous Z-climb while the Pro / Cat 1-2 will continue down Florida canyon and up the Pershing single-track climb.   Both courses re-join at the top of the Z-climb.

Note for Cat 3 riders — The left turn up the Z-climb comes quick when you’re smoking down the Florida canyon single-track.  We strongly recommend you pre-ride the course to be familiar with this left turn — it’d be a bummer to over-shoot it and have to back-track — or, worse to add mileage, climbing and time by taking the Pershing climb.

We’ll have this marked with arrows and a they’ll be a Course Marshall at that turn — but neither of those will help if you’re not ready for it.

*All categories will start with 2 parade laps on the Velodrome lead out by motor-pace.

To keep things competitive each category will complete the following laps around the courses:

    Category Pro/1: 7 laps Pershing Course (~22 miles)
    Category 2: 5 laps (~16 miles) Pershing Course
    Category 3 (Beginner): 3 laps Z-Climb Course (~10 miles)

*Course details / routing subject to change.
notes:
Start Time | 7:00 pm

Course open for pre-ride at 5:00pm
Safety

In addition to all of the normal safety rules associated with a USAC event we are also implementing the following:

    You must race with both a light on your bars and a light on your helmet.
    Total lumens of your setup must be 1000 or more.  Light output will be measured at event registration.
    Crossing the finish line without your lights working will result in an automatic DNF, no exceptions.

Race Fees

Included in your $55 entry fee is the following:

    Race Entry
    Chip Timing
    Exclusive Event T-Shirt For The First 50 Registrants!
    Goodie Bag
    Special Ninja Night Race Badge Of Honor
    Post-Race Tamales For All Riders
    Raffle Ticket
    Live Band Playing In The In-field (Jesse Eisner)
            Esse Jeisner Retakes the States
            Alexander and the Ninja Assassins Verses the Narcicist Robots

We are also excited to offer cash prizes for our pro and cat 1 riders.
directions:
Start/Finish:  San Diego Velodrome Entrance (Morley Field)

Approximate address:  2972-3268 Florida Dr, San Diego, CA 92104

title: Back Abbey/Coates Cyclery Year End Training Ride
description: This is a non-competitive training ride for USCF licensed racers riding counter-clockwise around the "Many Hills" loop in the Claremont/Laverne/San Dimas/Covina area. The event is intended for experienced riders and the pace will be moderate with several moderate but short climbs. The ride will begin and end at the Coffee Bean on Indian Hill in Claremont. The course route may be changed at the start by the organizer due to weather, traffic or event turn out.
course: An approximately 30 mile loop through neighboring cities. Traffic should be light to moderate on secondary and primary roads with some sections requiring single file riding.
registration: Registration will be located in the open public area adjacent to the Coffee Bean, known affectionately as "Smokers Alley" on Indian Hill Ave. in downtown Claremont. Registration will be open from 6:45am to 7:00am.  There is no online or pre-registration for this event.
notes: All USCF rules apply. Helmet’s are mandatory at all times while on your bike. Shirts must cover shoulders. No fixed gears and no recumbents. Tandems are permitted but both riders must register and be USCF licensed. Route is open to traffic and all traffic laws apply. Riders are responsible for their own safety with traffic and other bikes.
directions: From the East or West, exit at Towne Ave. off the 210 Fwy. Go South to Foothill Blvd. and turn left. Continue East until Indian Hill Ave and turn right. The ride will begin at the Coffee Bean on the West side of the road between W. Bonita Ave. and W. 2nd St.
